  "text": "In agreement with previous reports [CITATION_1] ), SLR-inducing doses of both blockers reduced CR latency and changed the temporal profile of CRs, which frequently peaked before the US onset (Figs. 2A, 3A) . GZ reduced CR amplitude (Figs. 2 and 5) when measured relative to the eyelid position before application of the CS. Effects of PTX on CR amplitude were less pronounced, ranging from a small decrease in Experiment #1 (Fig. 5) to no change in Experiment #2 (Fig. 8) . On the other hand, CR peaks measured relative to the maximally open eye, increased following both drugs and in both experiments (Figs. 5, 8 ). These seemingly contradictory effects were due to a drug-induced tonic eyelid closure. Following drug injections, CRs were evoked on a background of tonic eyelid closure and the same or smaller blinks resulted in absolute eyelid closure larger than baseline blinks recorded before injections or those recorded after control.",
